<subSubSection id="C37C44BD9279D924FF12FC6368ECFB91" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD917369279D924FF12FC6368ECFB91" blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">
<emphasis id="B912CB249279D924FF12FC636D6FFC01" bold="true" box="[199,335,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C666CB59279D924FE83FC636EB3FC01" authority="Lima, 2018" authorityName="Lima" authorityYear="2018" box="[342,659,980,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilianus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B912CB249279D924FE83FC636EB3FC01" box="[342,659,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Simothraulopsis gracilianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A221765F9279D924FD4EFC636ED5FC01" box="[667,757,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B912CB249279D924FD4EFC636ED5FC01" bold="true" box="[667,757,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
has distinctive penis lobes in relation to the other species of the genus. The inner margins of penis lobes are basally parallel and divergent distally, and the outer margins are strongly curved. The apical spines are directed to the midline of the styliger plate as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C666CB59279D924FB50FBAA696DFBD9" authorityName="Mariano" authorityYear="2010" box="[1157,1357,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diamantinensis">
<emphasis id="B912CB249279D924FB50FBAA696DFBD9" box="[1157,1357,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">S. diamantinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C666CB59279D924FA52FBAA6D22FBB4" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eurybasis">
<emphasis id="B912CB249279D924FA52FBAA6D22FBB4" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">S. eurybasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in 
<taxonomicName id="4C666CB59279D924FE82FBF76DD3FBB4" authorityName="Lima" authorityYear="2018" box="[343,499,1087,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilianus">
<emphasis id="B912CB249279D924FE82FBF76DD3FBB4" box="[343,499,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">S. gracilianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the spines are longer (approximately half of the total length of penis lobes) while in 
<taxonomicName id="4C666CB59279D924FF42FBD26D7DFB91" authorityName="Mariano" authorityYear="2010" box="[151,349,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diamantinensis">
<emphasis id="B912CB249279D924FF42FBD26D7DFB91" box="[151,349,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">S. diamantinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C666CB59279D924FE46FBD26E39FB91" box="[403,537,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eurybasis">
<emphasis id="B912CB249279D924FE46FBD26E39FB91" box="[403,537,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">S. eurybasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the spines are less than the half of total length of penis lobes.
</paragraph>
